C++ Notes
*********************

declaration statements - int x;
 assignment statements - x = 5;
     output statements - std::cout << x;
            expression - x = 2 + 3;
              function - collection of statements that executes sequentially.
               library - a collection of precompiled code that has been packaged
                         for reuse in different programs
                object - a piece of memory that can be used to store values
              variable - an object with a name
              l-values - a value that has an address in memory ( found on the left side in an assignment )
              r-values - any value that can be assigned to an l-value ( found on the right side of an assingment )
            definition - allocating a portion of memory for a variable
            assignment - placing a value in a variables memory address
         initalization`- defining and assigning a value to a variable at the same time


*** C/C++ does not initialize variables with a default value, so it will be what ever is already in that address ***


Sample Program - Hello World!
*********************

/*
 * This is multi-lined comments
 */

#include <iostream>     // this is a preprocessor directive

using namespace std;    // removes the need to type std::cout etc.

int two_plus_two()
{
    return 2 + 2;
}

int main()
{
    cout << "Hello, World!";
    two_plus_two();
    return 0;
}



Cout, Cin, and Endl
*********************

Found in iostream library 
#include <iostream>;

cout -  Print to the console
        std::cout << "Hello, World!";

 cin -  Read in from the console and assign to a variable
